            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ayan Gallo\u2019s story is a blend of flavors, much like the cocktails he designs. Born in Daly City to a Filipino mother and an Italian-American father, his childhood was a vibrant fusion of cultures. Family gatherings were loud, fragrant affairs, filled with lumpia and lasagna, boisterous laughter, and the unspoken language of shared hospitality. This upbringing instilled in him a deep appreciation for how food and drink can forge connection and create memory.\n\nHe attended San Francisco State University, pursuing a practical degree in Hospitality Management. It was a part-time bartending job in the Mission, however, that became his true education. He quickly graduated from pouring beers to mastering classics, fascinated by the history and alchemy in every shaker. He realized that a cocktail wasn't just a drink; it was a story in a glass, a carefully balanced experience.\n\nAfter graduating, a key turning point came when a struggling but ambitious restaurant in Hayes Valley hired him not just to tend bar, but to completely overhaul their beverage program. This was his chance to create. He introduced inventive, artisanal cocktails that earned critical praise, transforming the bar into a destination. At 34, he is now the Cocktail Program Director for a small but prestigious restaurant group, a position that allows him both stability and creative freedom.\n\nAyan lives in a classic, slightly-too-expensive one-bedroom apartment in Hayes Valley, just a ten-minute walk from his primary venue. His daily routine involves a morning walk to a local cafe, afternoons spent experimenting with infusions and syrups, and long nights orchestrating the perfect service. His social circle is tight-knit, composed mostly of fellow industry professionals who understand the demanding lifestyle.\n\nHe feels deeply woven into the fabric of his neighborhood and the city itself. San Francisco is the only backdrop he can imagine for his craft. His ultimate dream is to open his own small, intimate bar\u2014a place that reflects his unique heritage, perhaps serving amaro alongside calamansi-infused gin. It would be a space dedicated to craft, conversation, and the simple, profound act of welcoming someone in."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten years old, navigating the beautiful chaos of a family party. His Lola gave him a tray of Sarsi, and his Nonna gave him one of Chinotto. He felt a surge of importance weaving through the raucous laughter, offering uncles and cousins a glass. The simple act of providing a drink and receiving a warm smile felt like a secret power. It was his first taste of hospitality, the realization that you could serve someone joy in a glass. This memory became the foundation of his craft.\n\n2.\nHe was 20, working a slow Tuesday at that first bartending job in the Mission. An old regular asked for a Sazerac, a drink Ayan had only read about. As he rinsed the glass with absinthe and carefully stirred the rye, he felt a hush fall over his world. This wasn't just mixing; it was a ritual, a piece of history being summoned. In the precise movements, he felt a shift inside him. A part-time job suddenly felt like a potential life, and his fascination transformed into a deep reverence.\n\n3.\nHe still remembers standing alone in the pre-service quiet of the Hayes Valley bar, the glow of his phone illuminating his face. The first big review had just dropped. The critic specifically praised his cocktail\u2014\"The Daly City,\" a mix of amaro and calamansi. It wasn't just validation for a drink; it felt like praise for his entire story. In that moment, he knew that his mixed heritage wasn't just his past, but the very soul of his future creations.\n\n4.\nIt was 2 AM on a winter night, walking the ten minutes home from work. A heavy fog rolled through Hayes Valley, swallowing sound and softening the streetlights into halos. He passed Patricia\u2019s Green, seeing the vague shapes of the sculptures against the distant, glowing dome of City Hall. In that cool, damp silence, he felt an overwhelming sense of peace and belonging. It cemented his conviction that this city wasn't just a setting for his life; it was an essential part of him.\n\n5.\nLast year, after a devastating Saturday night service, he and his two closest friends\u2014a chef and a sommelier\u2014were crammed into his tiny apartment kitchen. They were sharing lukewarm beers and deconstructing every mistake. An impossibly cynical joke was made, and the three of them were seized by helpless, hysterical laughter that left them breathless. In that exhausted, delirious moment, Ayan felt an unshakeable sense of camaraderie. This was his chosen family, and they were the reason he could endure it all."
